sease, Kathleen returned to the letters, where she rediscovered the evocative image of a tiny, bright meadow bird perched precariously on a blade of elephant grass. That image – of simultaneous tension, fragility, power, and resilience – sustained her over the years that she used the letters as memory prompts in a larger strategy to keep her intellectually gifted mother alive. Deftly woven of excerpts from their correspondence, conversations, journal entries, and email updates, Bird-Bent Grass is a complex and moving exploration of memory, illness, and immigration; friendship, conflict, resilience, and forgiveness; cross-cultural communication, the ethics of international development, and letter-writing as a technology of intimacy. Throughout, it reflects on the imperative and fleeting business of being alive and loving others while they’re ours to hold.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlzheimer's diseasexPatientsvBiography. 0aAlzheimer's diseasexPatientsxFamily relationships. 0aAlzheimer's disease. 0aLetter writing, French. 0aLetter writing. 0aMothers and daughterszCanadavBiography. 0aPatients. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aEthnography. 4aFamily & Relationships. 4aLife Writing. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh  aAlzheimer’s Disease.  aCanada.  aNetherlands.  aUganda.  acivil war.  aconflict.  acorrespondence.  across-cultural communication.  across-cultural identity.  adeath.  adementia.  adying.  aidentity deformation.  aidentity formation.  ainternational development.  aletter writing.  amemory loss.  amother-daughter relationship.  apost-WWII immigration.  aprogressive theology.  aresilience.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package: